[4] Diarrhea - Zimbabwe
Date: Wed 19 Aug 2015
Source: Newsday [edited]
https://www.newsday.co.zw/2015/08/19/water-shortages-fuel-typhoid/


Nearly 300 000 cases of diarrheal disease have been reported since the beginning of 2015 and 323 deaths recorded in the same period, a weekly disease surveillance report from the Ministry of Health has revealed. The report indicated that 60 percent of the victims were children under 5 years of age. Erratic water supplies have seen many people resorting to unclean water sources which are a breeding ground for waterborne diseases like typhoid and dysentery.

Harare City Council's director of health services Prosper Chonzi told NewsDay that they had noted an increase in diarrheal cases at most council clinics. "People are not getting water 24 hours and even though the situation has slightly improved, the shortages are still unacceptable," said the director. Chonzi also said most of these cases were being recorded from new resettlements like Hopley and Hatcliffe Extension which did not have access to proper sanitation.

"In most of these areas there are no ablution facilities and people use pit latrines while others use the bush toilet," he said. He also said the situation was worse in rural areas where 34 percent of the people had no access to toilets.

[Byline: Phyllis Mbanje]

