[5] Cholera - India (Chandigarh)
Date: Wed 12 Aug 2015
Source: Hindustan Times [edited]
http://www.hindustantimes.com/chandigarh/seven-of-23-water-samples-from-cholera-hit-manimajra-fail-test/article1-1379041.aspx


The real culprit behind the cholera outbreak in Manimajra is contaminated water; this was revealed by the health department after examination of water samples. According to director of health services, Chandigarh, Dr VK Gagneja, as many as 7 out of 23 water samples collected from the area have failed the bacteriological test. He said the hydrogen sulfide test, which is a bacteriological examination, was performed on the samples and it was found that the water was unfit for human consumption. He said they have also informed the MC [municipal corporation] officials about the test reports.

City mayor Poonam Sharma on Tuesday visited Manimajra hospital to take stock of the situation and meet the patients. The mayor said that she that she will also visit New Indira Colony and other parts of Manimajra along with MC officials on Wednesday morning, 12 Aug 2015, to check the water supply lines and water disposal lines in the area. She further instructed the water supply officials to supply water only through tankers to the affected areas in Manimajra. She said the MC will extend all kinds of help to the cholera patients.

The MC officials had on Monday, 10 Aug 2015, claimed that the samples they had collected from the area were found fit for human consumption. When contacted, MC superintending engineer NP Sharma said, "We had taken samples from our water pipelines, but those were found fit for human consumption. We have also increased the quantity of chlorine in the water. The samples that failed must have been taken from the victims' houses." However, the health officials said the MC doesn't conduct bacteriological studies of water. This study helps to [detect] the bacterium in the water that causes cholera.

4 fresh cases of cholera were reported on Tuesday, 11 Aug 2015, with total number of cases reaching 12. Apart from cholera, around 50 cases of mild/severe diarrhea were also reported. The health department's door-to-door survey, in which people suffering from mild diarrhoea are being treated on the spot, continued even on Tuesday.

