[6] Cholera - Nepal (Katmandu)
Date: Mon 17 Aug 2015
Source: Prensa Latina [machine trans, edited]
http://prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&idioma=1&id=4065481&Itemid=1


20 cases of cholera were detected recently in the capital, a figure that could increase with the arrival of heavy rains associated with the monsoon season, a medical source revealed today, 17 Aug 2015. After several tests, 20 cases were confirmed as reported to The Himalayan Times by the director of the Division of Disease Control and Epidemiology of the Department of Health in Kathmandu, Dr. Baburam Marasini.

Contaminated water is the main cause of the spread of the disease. We advise the population to maintain adequate sanitation and hygiene
to prevent an outbreak, he warned. We can prevent a pandemic if we boil water, highlighted Marasini. He explained that patients were admitted to various hospitals, where they receive appropriate treatment.

With the arrival of the monsoon, the Kathmandu Valley is increasingly vulnerable to cholera, a virulent disease caused by ingestion of food or water contaminated with the bacterium _Vibrio cholerae, reported The Himalayan Times.

International organizations like the UN and national experts warned of an outbreak of cholera and other infectious diseases as a result of
earthquakes on 25 Apr 2015 and 12 May 2015 that left nearly 8900 dead.

